Name: Gavin Lee

Description:
libmythread.c is an implemented library in C. It is a library that provides 
threading managment, mutex locks and condition variables. The library supports cooperative
and premptive scheduling by context switching and preventing interrupts with a global variable.


DESIGN
------
Each thread is represented by a node in a doubley linked, linked list. ThreadInit()
Must be the first call to the library in order to initialize the linked list. 
threadCreate() - creates a thread by adding an element to the linked list and switching to that thread before returning
                Each thread is started by setting the stack pointer to the myThreadHandler() function
                that runs the thread by running the thread's function pointer and then calling threadExit() when it 
                finishes.
threadYield() - switches to another ready thread and sets the status to the calling thread to ready
threadJoin() - searches the LL for a given thread and then the calling thread waits for 
                that thread to finish by calling threadExit. It then stores that threads result
                into the result if it is not NULL. This function also removes the LL element that exited.
threadExit() - last call by each thread. It sets the calling thread's status to Exited and stores its function's result
                in its result. Then if there are threads waiting on the exited thread, each of those threads are set to 
                ready. Then it switches to the next ready thread
lockCreate() - Creates a mutex lock and returns a pointer to that lock
lockDestroy() - frees the memory associated with the lock struct
threadLock() - the calling thread waits until it is able to access the lock specified. If the lock that the thread
              is locked, it switches to another ready thread.
threadUnlock() - Unlocks the lock and then sets a waiting thread (if there are any) to ready.
condvarCreate() - creates a conditional variable
condvarDestroy() - frees a conditional variable
threadWait() - This function adds the current thread to the conditional variable's waiting list and then unlocks the lock
                then mark the calling thread as waiting and then switch to next ready thread
threadSignal() - signals thread wait to stop waiting and allow a thread through

The main thread is treated as thread 0 with no allocated stack.
Thread stacks are freed by other threads after exit, not by the exiting
thread itself, since a thread cannot safely free its own stack.

KNOWN PROBLEMS
--------------
No known problems

COMPILING
--------------
The thread library can be used by using make to create the libmythreads.o file
$(Compiler_Name) -Wall -g -c libmythreads.c -o libmythreads.o 

Then compile your test using
$(Compiler_Name) -Wall -g -o test_name test.c libmythreads.o
